Model fitting and calibration

Forrest W. Crawford

Overview

Suppose we have formulated a dynamic model for a particular problem of interest. We observe some data corresponding to model compartments.

Our goal is to use the data to learn about the parameters of our model, so that its dynamics closely approximate the data.

Our hope is that if we use data to learn about the dyanmics of the model (internal validity), we can change some of the parameters or structure of the model and get valid estimates of what would happen under counterfactual scenarios (external validity).

Formalism and notation

Suppose \(\hat y_i\) is a data point, observed at time \(t_i\), for \(i=1,\ldots,n\). Suppose we have formulated a model, that captures the mechanism of interest that produces the data. Let \(\theta\) be a parameter vector for the model, and let the model output with \(\theta\) be \(y_i(t,\theta)\). This is the prediction with a specific value of \(t\) and \(\theta\) plugged in.

We want to learn about a parameter vector \(\theta\). How should we do this? By choosing \(\theta\) to make the model output \(y_i(t_i|theta)\) look like the observed data \(\hat y_i\) for times \(t_1,\ldots,t_n\).

What does “look like” mean? What does it mean for two numbers to be “close together”? There are many answers to this question, but we will take the simplest one here.

Notation: in general we will use Greek letters for parameters that we want to calibrate or fit: \(\alpha\), \(\beta\), \(\gamma\), \(\theta\), \(\epsilon\).

Least squares

Fitting deterministic models by least squares

Consider the general “loss” function \[ L(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^n (y(t_i|\theta) - \hat y_i)^2 \]

This is a sum of differences between the model output \(y(t_i|\theta)\) and the observation \(\hat y_i\), squared. Why squared? Because squaring this difference makes the result positive, and gives larger values to larger deviations.

\(L(\theta)\) is big when the model fits the data badly, and near zero when it fits the data well.

We want to choose \(\theta\) to make this loss function \(L(\theta)\) as small as possible. The value of \(\theta\) that makes \(L(\theta)\) smallest will be our estimate of \(\theta\).

Example: deterministic SI model

Example: Suppose we have a SI system characterized by the deterministic ODE \[ \frac{dI}{dt} = \beta S(t) I(t) \] and \(N = S(t) + I(t)\) is known. Recall that for known \(I(0)=i_0\), we can solve for \(I(t)\) exactly at time points \(t_1,\ldots,t_n\). For a particular value of \(\beta\), call this solution \(I(t,\beta)\).

Suppose we observe the number of infected individuals \(\hat{I}(t_i)\) at times \(0,t_1,\ldots,t_n\). We wish to use the observed data to estimate \(\beta\) by making the model output \(I(t_i,\beta)\) as close as possible to the real data \(\hat{I}(t_i)\). The loss function is \[ L(\beta) = \sum_{j=1}^n (\hat I_j - I(t_j,\beta))^2 \] where \(I(t_j,\beta)\) is the values of \(I(t)\) at \(t_j\) using parameter value \(\beta\) obtained by numerical solution. The value of \(\beta\) that minimizes \(L(\beta)\) is our estimate of \(\beta\).

Illustration: deterministic SI model

Let’s generate data from the deterministic SI model, and add some “noise” to the infection output. Then we will try to estimate \(\beta\) using the recipe outlined above.

I_soln = function(t,beta) {
  beta*I0*exp(beta * t) / (beta + beta*I0*(exp(beta*t) - 1))
}

loss = function(I_obs,beta) {
  sum(( I_soln(ts,beta) - I_obs)^2 )
}

I0 = 0.01
bet = 0.6
ts = seq(1,15,by=0.3)
Is = I_soln(ts,bet)
Is_noise = pmax(0,Is + rnorm(length(ts), 0, 0.1))
par(mar=c(4,4.5,1,1))
plot(ts,Is_noise, ylim=c(0,1), ylab=expression(hat(I)(t)), xlab="Time", main="Raw data: number infected", bty="n")

Illustration: loss function

bets = seq(0.01,1, by=0.01)
loss_values = sapply(bets, function(b)loss(Is_noise,b))
plot(bets, loss_values, ylab=expression(L(beta)), xlab=expression(beta), bty="n", type="l", lwd=2)
bet_hat = bets[which.min(loss_values)]
arrows(bet_hat, (min(loss_values)+max(loss_values))/2, 
       bet_hat, min(loss_values))
text(bet_hat, (min(loss_values)+max(loss_values))/2, bet_hat, pos=3)

Illustration: model fit

Is_fitted = I_soln(ts,bet_hat)
par(mar=c(4,4.5,1,1))
plot(ts,Is_noise, ylim=c(0,1), ylab=expression(hat(I)(t)), xlab="Time", bty="n")
lines(ts,Is_fitted,col="red", lwd=2)
lines(ts,Is, col="green", lwd=2)
legend(1,1.0, c("Data", "True model prediction", "Fitted model prediction"), col=c("black", "green", "red"), pch=c(1,NA,NA), lwd=c(NA,2,2), lty=c(NA,1,1))

Maximum likelihood

Fitting deterministic models with statistical error distributions

Deterministic models produce a single trajectory for model compartments. But real data are noisy and bumpy. We can hypothesize a probability model for how error enters the model output and use that model to construct the loss function.

For example, some researchers assume that the observed count is a Poisson random variable whose mean is the true compartment value in the deterministic model. For the \(I\) compartment, \[ \hat{I}(t) \sim \text{Poisson}(I(t,\beta)) \] Sometimes the error is modeled as Gaussian, or normal, \[ \hat{I}(t) \sim \text{Normal}(I(t,\beta), \sigma^2) \]

Maximum likelihood

Let’s look at the Poisson case. The likelihood is the product of Poisson probabilities

\[ \text{Likelihood}(\beta) = \prod_{i=1}^n \frac{I(t_i,\beta)^{\hat{I}(t_i)} \exp[-I(t_i,\beta)]}{\hat{I}(t_i)!} \]

and the loss function is the negative log-likelihood,

\[ L(\beta) = \sum_{i=1}^n \hat{I}(t_i) \log(I(t_i,\beta)) - I(t_i,\beta) \]

where \(I(t,\beta)\) is the solution to the system.

Fitting more complicated models

Once you have a model that you can solve (on a computer) for a given set of input parameter values and you have defined a loss function that tells you what a “good” set of parameters looks like, you need to find the parameters that minimize the loss function. However, not all loss functions have a unique minimum.

When there is more than one or two unknown parameters, it can be difficult to visualize or search the space of values for the minimum of the loss function.

In this situation, you can’t just look at the loss function evaluated at several values of the parameter. You need to use a computer program to find the value of \(\theta\) that minimizes \(L(\theta)\).

R provides several functions for nonlinear optimization, but the most useful is nlm. Here is an example:

Using nlm

Here is a SIR trajectory with noise added

library(deSolve)
sir.model <- function (t, x, params) { 
  S <- x[1] 
  I <- x[2] 
  R <- x[3] 
  with( as.list(params), { 
    dS <- -beta*S*I
    dI <- beta*S*I-gamma*I
    dR <- gamma*I
    dx <- c(dS,dI,dR) 
    list(dx) 
  })}

  times <- seq(0,120,by=1)
  params <- c(beta=0.5,gamma=1/7)
  xstart <- c(S=9999/10000,I=1/10000,R=0)
  out <- as.data.frame( lsoda(xstart, times, sir.model, params) )
  S_obs = rnorm(length(times),out$S,sd=0.1)
  I_obs = rnorm(length(times),out$I,sd=0.1)
  R_obs = rnorm(length(times),out$R,sd=0.1)

  plot(out$time, I_obs, ylab="Population proportion", xlab="Time", pch=16, bty="n", ylim=c(0,1), col="red") 
  points(out$time, S_obs, pch=16, col="green")
  points(out$time, R_obs, pch=16, col="blue")
  legend(100,0.5, c("S(t)", "I(t)", "R(t)"), pch=16, col=c("green", "red", "blue"))

Fitting

loss = function(params) {
  names(params) = c("beta", "gamma")
  out = as.data.frame( lsoda(xstart, times, sir.model, params) )
  sum( (out$S - S_obs)^2 + (out$I - I_obs)^2 + (out$R - R_obs)^2 )
}

fit = nlm(loss, p=c(0.3,0.2), stepmax=0.05)

  betahat = fit$estimate[1]
  gammahat = fit$estimate[2]

  out_fitted = as.data.frame( lsoda(xstart, times, sir.model, c(beta=betahat,gamma=gammahat)))

  plot(out$time, I_obs, ylab="Population proportion", xlab="Time", pch=16, bty="n", ylim=c(0,1), col="red") 
  points(out$time, S_obs, pch=16, col="green")
  points(out$time, R_obs, pch=16, col="blue")


  lines(out$time, out$S, col="green", lwd=2)
  lines(out$time, out$I, col="red", lwd=2) 
  lines(out$time, out$R, col="blue", lwd=2)


  lines(out$time, out_fitted$S, col="green", lwd=2, lty="dashed")
  lines(out$time, out_fitted$I, col="red", lwd=2, lty="dashed") 
  lines(out$time, out_fitted$R, col="blue", lwd=2, lty="dashed")

  legend(80,0.8, c("S(t)", "I(t)", "R(t)", "S(t) (estimated)", "I(t) (estimated)", "R(t) (estimated)"), col=c("green", "red", "blue"), lwd=2, lty=c(1,1,1,2,2,2))

Non-identifiable parameters

Sometimes you do not have enough data to tell you about some of the parameters in your model.

In this case, in order to use the model to make predictions, you will need to set these parameters to particular values. There are several strategies for doing this:

  1. Make up values that seem reasonable
  2. Pick values from the scientific literature
  3. Pick an interval, or probability distribution, in which you think the parameters lie

When you do this, your model output may depend a lot on which values you use, and it is important to assess the sensitivity of your model to these parameter assumptions.

Sensitivity analysis

Sensitivity analysis is the process

Let \(Y(\theta)\) be the output of your model with parameter value \(\theta\). When you’re not sure about the exact value of \(\theta\) you want to use, you can use many values of \(\theta\). Suppose you have candidate values of \(\theta\), \(\theta_1,\ldots,\theta_m\).

Then generate model output \(Y(\theta_1),\ldots,Y(\theta_m)\), and report the variation in these outcomes.

Not covered

There is a whole scientific field concerned with getting good estimates of \(\theta\) given data. It is called statistics.

  • Frequentist methods
  • Bayesian methods
  • Probabilistic representations of uncertainty
